      "title": "Module 1: The misattribution trap",
      "text": "Here's the trap, and it's subtle. When something goes wrong now, a thought tends to surface: \"At a moment like this, I'd have had a cigarette.\" True — you would have. But watch what your mind does next: it quietly blames the distress on the absence of the cigarette, as if smoking would have solved the problem. It wouldn't have. When you were a smoker, the broken-down car, the argument, the bad news were all exactly as bad — you just lit a cigarette and the car was still broken. The cigarette never touched the actual problem. It only ever quieted the monster.\n\nSo on a hard day, the smoker's instinct creates an impossible bind: you feel bad because you can't have the thing you believe would help, and you'd feel worse if you had it (because you'd have restarted the addiction on top of the original problem). The way out is to see clearly that the cigarette was never a solution to anything except withdrawal — a withdrawal you no longer have. The bad day is real; smoking was never its cure."
