      "title": "Module 2: Don't let \"quitting\" take the blame",
      "text": "When you're free and a bad day hits, there's a tendency to pin everything on the quit: \"Ugh, everything's harder since I stopped.\" It isn't. You had bad days as a smoker too — plenty of them, or you wouldn't have wanted to stop. Life has ups and downs on its own schedule, entirely independent of your smoking status. Watch for your mind filing ordinary bad-day distress under \"evidence that quitting was a mistake.\" That's a distortion, and naming it strips its power: \"This is just a hard day. It has nothing to do with not smoking. Smoking wouldn't fix it, and being free isn't causing it.\"\n\nIn fact, you're now better equipped to handle hard days — physically steadier without the drug fraying your nerves, and mentally clearer without the background insecurity it installed. The non-smoker doesn't just cope as well as the smoker on a bad day; they cope better."
